  "opinion": "As a 19-year-old woman growing up in Milan with parents who both have advanced degrees, I’ve witnessed firsthand how science education often feels like a monochrome landscape—where the stories of discovery are told through the lens of a few dominant voices. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers; it’s about the silence that surrounds the contributions of women who’ve shaped fields from quantum mechanics to ecology. My parents’ conversations about their work often highlight how women have been systematically excluded from leadership roles, even when their research is groundbreaking. For instance, I’ve read about how Marie Curie’s Nobel Prize-winning work was overshadowed by her husband’s name, a pattern that repeats in many scientific histories. This isn’t just historical—it’s a living reality. In my city, science clubs and university programs still tend to attract more men, and I’ve seen how this affects my peers. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of top-down policies that feel impersonal, we need grassroots initiatives that reflect the diversity of our communities. My own creative hobbies—like photography and hiking—teach me that science isn’t just about labs and equations; it’s about curiosity and connection. I believe we should create spaces where women can explore science without fear of judgment, using storytelling and hands-on projects to make it relatable. In a world where neuroticism is high and creativity is my strength, I see the power in fostering environments that celebrate all voices. The gender gap in science is a mirror of our societal biases, and closing it requires empathy, not just data.",
